#Approach:

Approach:
Ye problem sliding window + HashMap se solve hoti hai.

1. Window [left ... right] maintain karte hain.
2. Right pointer ko aage badhate hue current character ki frequency map me store karte hain.
3. Agar map.size() > k ho jaaye,
   matlab window me k se zyada distinct characters aa gaye,
   to left pointer aage badha ke window shrink karte hain.
4. Shrink karte time left character ki frequency kam karte hain,
   aur agar frequency 0 ho jaaye to map se remove kar dete hain.
5. Har valid window (map.size() <= k) ke liye maxLen update karte rehte hain.

Main idea:
Hume longest substring chahiye jisme at most k distinct characters ho,
isliye window ko expand bhi karte hain aur invalid hote hi shrink bhi karte hain.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(k) / O(Alphabet)

#Code:

import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int kDistinctChar(String s, int k) {
        if (k == 0) return 0;

        int n = s.length();
        int left = 0, right = 0;
        int maxLen = 0;
        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        while (right < n) {
            char ch = s.charAt(right);
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);

            while (map.size() > k) {
                char leftChar = s.charAt(left);
                map.put(leftChar, map.get(leftChar) - 1);

                if (map.get(leftChar) == 0) {
                    map.remove(leftChar);
                }
                left++;
            }

            maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, right - left + 1);
            right++;
        }

        return maxLen;
    }
}
